how to configure LinPhone App to cisco 4321 Call Manager Express

To connect Linphone (softphone) to a Cisco 4321 running Call Manager Express (CME), you’re essentially registering Linphone as a third-party SIP endpoint. It works, but Cisco CME is picky—so the key is matching SIP credentials + registrar settings exactly.

Here’s a practical, working approach.
🧩 1. Configure Cisco CME (on your 4321)

First, make sure CME is acting as a SIP registrar (this is mandatory):

voice service voip
 allow-connections sip to sip
 sip
  registrar server

This enables SIP phone registration on CME
📞 Create SIP extension (DN)

voice register dn 1
 number 1001
 name Linphone1

👤 Create SIP user (important for Linphone login)

voice register pool 1
 id mac 1234.5678.9ABC   ! (dummy MAC for softphone)
 number 1 dn 1
 username linphone password cisco123
 codec g711ulaw
 dtmf-relay sip-notify

👉 Key point:

    username + password here = what Linphone will use

    CME uses digest authentication for SIP devices

🌐 Global SIP settings

voice register global
 mode cme
 source-address 192.168.1.1 port 5060
 max-dn 10
 max-pool 10
 authenticate register
 create profile

👉 source-address = IP of your router (IMPORTANT)
📱 2. Configure Linphone

Open Linphone → Add SIP account → use:
Basic settings

    Username / Auth ID: linphone

    Password: cisco123

    Domain / SIP Server: 192.168.1.1 (your router IP)

    Transport: UDP (default)

Advanced (if needed)

    Proxy: same as domain

    Port: 5060

    Registration: enabled

🔁 3. Dialing rules (often forgotten)

On CME, you need dial-peers or simple extension dialing:

dial-peer voice 100 voip
 destination-pattern 1...
 session protocol sipv2
 session target ipv4:192.168.1.1
 codec g711ulaw

🧪 4. Verify registration

Run on router:

show voice register pool all
show sip-ua register status

You should see Linphone as REGISTERED.
⚠️ Common Issues (very important)
❌ Registration fails

    Wrong username/password (most common)

    Missing authenticate register

    Wrong domain (must match router IP)

❌ No audio

    NAT issue (if outside LAN)

    Codec mismatch → use G.711 u-law

❌ Can’t dial

    Missing dial-peer

    No dial-plan configured

🧠 Key Insight

Cisco CME treats Linphone as a generic SIP phone, not a native Cisco device.
That means:

    No auto-provisioning (manual only)

    You must define username/password + DN binding

    CME acts as both registrar and PBX

✅ Simple Working Example Summary
Component	Value
Extension	1001
Username	linphone
Password	cisco123
SIP Server	192.168.1.1
Port	5060

