That debug output is the smoking gun.

    SIP/2.0 482 Loop Detected

This is not a credential problem, not MAC, not even basic connectivity.

👉 It means:

    🔴 Your router is sending the REGISTER request… back to itself

So CME sees its own message looping and rejects it.
💥 Why this is happening

This line in your config is the culprit:

dial-peer voice 72 voip
 destination-pattern 72...
 session target ipv4:10.72.100.8

👉 You are explicitly telling the router:

    “Any SIP request for 72xx → send it to 10.72.100.8 (which is… me)”

So the flow becomes:

    Linphone → REGISTER to CME

    CME → matches dial-peer

    CME → sends REGISTER to itself

    CME detects loop → ❌ 482 Loop Detected

🚨 Key insight

Dial-peers should NOT handle REGISTER messages.

But your config is interfering with SIP routing enough to cause this loop.
✅ FIX (this will solve your issue)
🔥 Remove the dial-peer

conf t
no dial-peer voice 72 voip

🧪 Then test again

Run:

debug ccsip messages

Try Linphone login again.
✅ Expected correct behavior

You should now see:

REGISTER →
401 Unauthorized →
REGISTER →
200 OK

👉 That means:

    CME accepted the registration

    Linphone should show “Registered”

🧠 Why this happened

Cisco CME:

    Handles REGISTER locally via registrar

    Uses dial-peers only for call routing

Your dial-peer forced:

    signaling → external routing → loop → rejection

📌 Important rule going forward

👉 Never point a dial-peer to the router’s own IP
unless you really know why (rare cases like B2BUA scenarios)
👍 After it works

If you want internal calling between extensions like 7271, you actually don’t need any dial-peer at all—CME handles it automatically.
🚀 If something still fails

Send the new debug after removing the dial-peer.
But honestly—this loop error is the root cause, and removing that dial-peer should fix your login immediately.

